Key observation

Any integer can be represented as a sum of powers of two (binary representation).

But we need exactly k terms.

That means:

The remainder must be ≥ k (since each term ≥ 1).

And the number of set bits in the remainder ≤ k (because we can split powers of two further into smaller ones).

Algorithm

Try all possible values of k (number of spells).

Compute rem = num1 - k * num2.

If rem < 0, skip.

If rem >= k and popcount(rem) <= k, then k works.

Return the smallest such k.

If none works → -1.

✅ Full C++ Code
cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int T; cin >> T;
    while (T--) {
        long long num1, num2;
        cin >> num1 >> num2;
        int ans = -1;

        for (int k = 1; k <= 60; k++) { // max 60 spells
            long long rem = num1 - k * num2;
            if (rem < 0) continue;
            int bits = __builtin_popcountll(rem);
            if (bits <= k && rem >= k) {
                ans = k;
                break;
            }
        }

        cout << ans << "\n";
    }
    return 0;
}
